Taylor meets west <PLACE continent="AF" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:30002777" id="Pl-13" mod="W" type="CONTINENT">African</PLACE> envoys on exile call

<TEXT>

<PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17865988" id="Pl-1" latLong="6.311°N 10.805°W" state="MO" type="PPLC">MONROVIA</PLACE>, Aug 2 (AFP)

<PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17866482" id="Pl-6" latLong="6.500°N 9.500°W" type="COUNTRY">Liberia</PLACE>'s embattled president, Charles Taylor, began meeting Saturday
with a west <PLACE continent="AF" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:30002777" id="Pl-14" mod="W" type="CONTINENT">African</PLACE> ministerial delegation which has travelled to
<PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17865988" id="Pl-2" latLong="6.311°N 10.805°W" state="MO" type="PPLC">Monrovia</PLACE> to demand he step down and head into exile.

Taylor and his vice-president Moses Blah met with a team led by
Mohamed ibn Chambas, executive secretary of the Economic Community of
West <PLACE continent="AF" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:30002777" id="Pl-15" mod="W" type="CONTINENT">African</PLACE> States (ECOWAS), at the president's official residence

in the besieged <PLACE country="LR" form="NOM" gazref="IGDB:17865988" id="Pl-17" latLong="6.311°N 10.805°W" state="MO" type="PPLC">city</PLACE>.

The <PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17866482" id="Pl-7" latLong="6.500°N 9.500°W" type="COUNTRY">Liberian</PLACE> leader had been expected to meet the ECOWAS party on
Friday, but failed to turn up, annoying some members of the
delegation.

Arriving at the meeting, Taylor angrily denied that he had tried to
avoid the envoys. &quot;I'm not running away,&quot; he said, accusing the media
of lying about his absence the previous day.

Aides claimed Taylor had travelled to the <PLACE id="Pl-355" type="FAC">port</PLACE> city of <PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17869263" id="Pl-18" latLong="5.881°N 10.047°W" state="GB" type="PPL">Buchanan</PLACE>, a
short distance south of the <PLACE country="LR" form="NOM" gazref="IGDB:17865988" id="Pl-11" latLong="6.311°N 10.805°W" state="MO" type="PPLC">capital</PLACE>, one of the frontlines in his war
with two rebel armies who control four fifths of the <PLACE country="LR" form="NOM" gazref="IGDB:17866482" id="Pl-10" latLong="6.500°N 9.500°W" type="COUNTRY">country</PLACE>.

The ECOWAS delegation included <PLACE country="GH" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17926607" id="Pl-19" latLong="8.000°N 2.000°W" type="COUNTRY">Ghana</PLACE>'s Foreign Minister Addo Akufo
Addo, the <PLACE country="NG" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17979109" id="Pl-20" latLong="10.000°N 8.000°E" type="COUNTRY">Nigerian</PLACE> minister for cooperation and integration Lawan
Gana Guba and the <PLACE country="TG" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:18500437" id="Pl-23" latLong="8.000°N 1.167°E" type="COUNTRY">Togolese</PLACE> defense minister General Assani Tidjani.

<PLACE country="NG" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17979109" id="Pl-21" latLong="10.000°N 8.000°E" type="COUNTRY">Nigeria</PLACE> has offered Taylor political asylum if he agrees to resign
his post and allow international mediators to broker an agreement to
end <PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17866482" id="Pl-8" latLong="6.500°N 9.500°W" type="COUNTRY">Liberia</PLACE>'s latest four-year bout of civil war.

A 1,500-strong advance guard of <PLACE country="NG" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17979109" id="Pl-22" latLong="10.000°N 8.000°E" type="COUNTRY">Nigerian</PLACE> peacekeepers is due to start
arriving in <PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17865988" id="Pl-3" latLong="6.311°N 10.805°W" state="MO" type="PPLC">Monrovia</PLACE> on Monday, and ECOWAS has given Taylor an
ultimatum that he must leave office within three days of the
soldiers' arrival.

But even as the warlord-turned-president arrived at his official
<PLACE id="Pl-347" type="FAC">residence</PLACE>, intense fighting was continuing on the frontline in the
<PLACE country="LR" form="NOM" gazref="IGDB:17865988" id="Pl-12" latLong="6.311°N 10.805°W" state="MO" type="PPLC">capital</PLACE>, an AFP reporter at the scene said.

<PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17866482" id="Pl-9" latLong="6.500°N 9.500°W" type="COUNTRY">Liberian</PLACE> government forces fought their way across two frontline
<PLACE id="Pl-348" type="FAC">bridges</PLACE> in the capital <PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17865988" id="Pl-4" latLong="6.311°N 10.805°W" state="MO" type="PPLC">Monrovia</PLACE> in what commanders said was an
offensive aimed a recapturing the <PLACE country="LR" form="NOM" gazref="IGDB:17865988" id="Pl-24" latLong="6.311°N 10.805°W" state="MO" type="PPLC">city</PLACE>'s rebel-held <PLACE id="Pl-346" type="FAC">port</PLACE>.


Loyalist troops crossed the two key <PLACE id="Pl-349" type="FAC">bridges</PLACE>, the <PLACE id="Pl-350" type="FAC">site</PLACE> of a two-week
standoff with rebels, under a heavy barrage of rocket and mortar fire
and entered <PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:20120641" id="Pl-25" latLong="6.631°N 10.250°W" state="MO" type="PPL">Via Town</PLACE>, a <PLACE country="LR" form="NOM" gazref="IGDB:20120641" id="Pl-26" latLong="6.631°N 10.250°W" state="MO" type="PPL">city district</PLACE> separating central <PLACE country="LR" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:17865988" id="Pl-5" latLong="6.311°N 10.805°W" mod="CENTRAL" state="MO" type="PPLC">Monrovia</PLACE>
from the <PLACE country="NG" form="NOM" id="Pl-28" state="GB" type="RGN">port area</PLACE>.

Several <PLACE id="Pl-354" type="FAC">houses</PLACE> could be seen burning in <PLACE country="LR" form="NOM" gazref="IGDB:20120641" id="Pl-27" latLong="6.631°N 10.250°W" state="MO" type="PPL">Via Town</PLACE> as the fighting
raged. Government officers on the ground said the offensive was aimed
at securing the <PLACE id="Pl-352" type="FAC">port</PLACE> to allow west <PLACE continent="AF" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:30002777" id="Pl-16" mod="W" type="CONTINENT">African</PLACE> peacekeepers to bring in
men and equipment.

